  }), "\n  "), "\n    ")), mdx("p", null, "My partner was also doing something similar but was using a concept that is not present in Flux, neither in Asp.Net MVC, which is middleware. The middleware is a function that listens to every action and can decide to opt in or not. Redux loops through all the middleware right before the action read the reducers. This means that it's pretty close to where the action creator is located. The main difference is that if we move the logic from the action creator to middleware naively we would end up having a lot of middleware. If you have 50 pages, with 50 action creators, this would result to 50 middlewares. It is also against the spirit of how to use middleware even if how to use middleware is not very documented or should I say opinionated. While you could in practice have a lot of middlewares, it becomes fast cumbersome. Middleware needs to be registered and that would end up having to register a lot of them which would also all be invoked on every action."), mdx("p", null, mdx("span", {
